                                    2. int hashCode() method
                                   ===========================

=> When we create object for a class then JVM will assign one unique hashcode for every object.
=> Using hashCode() method we can get hashCode of the object.
=> If we don't want to execute Object class hashCode() method then we can override hashCode() method in our class.

========
Example
========

package in.psa.dev;

public class Student {
	
	int id;
	String name;
	
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		
		Student s = new Student();
		s.id=101;
		s.name="sonu";
		System.out.println(s.hashCode());
		
		String s1 = new String("hi");
		System.out.println(s1);
	}
	
	public int hashCode() {
		return id;
	}
}


                            =========================================================
                                  3. boolean equals(Object obj ) method
                            =========================================================

=> equals() method is used to compare one object with another object and returns boolean value.
   If objects are same then it will return true otherwise it will return false value.

Note: Object class equals() method will compare address of the object not content.


package in.psa.dev;
import java.util.Objects;
public class Student {
	
	int id;
	String name;
	
	
	public Student(int id, String name) {

	this.id=id;
	this.name=name;
	
	}
	
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		
		
		Student s = new Student(101, "john");
		Student s1 = new Student(101, "john");
		
		System.out.println(s.equals(s1));//this is comparing the address
		System.out.println(s1 == s);//this is comparing the address
		
		
		String s2 = new String("sonu");
		String s3 = new String("sonu");
		
		System.out.println(s2.equals(s3)); // this is comparing the value
	
	}

	@Override
	public int hashCode() {
		return Objects.hash(id, name);
	}

	@Override
	public boolean equals(Object obj) {
		if (this == obj)
			return true;
		if (obj == null)
			return false;
		if (getClass() != obj.getClass())
			return false;
		Student other = (Student) obj;
		return id == other.id && Objects.equals(name, other.name);
	}
	

}


Note: In String class equals () method overriden to compare content of objects thats why in above program for String 
       we are getting "true " as a output. For student class it is checking address hence we are getting "false" as output.


=>  If we want to comapre cotnent of our student objects then we need to override below.


